The first week of Trump\'92s second term opened with a rush, not a drift. Power moved fast, by signature and decree. The pattern was clear: use the tools of the presidency to redraw who belongs, who is protected, and who can hold the executive to account. It was a week of first principles, tested in real time. Birthright citizenship, term limits, the neutrality of law, the independence of watchdogs, and the basic safety of dissent all came under pressure. The Democracy Clock, which had stood at 7:31 p.m. at the close of the previous term, now jumped forward to 7:55 p.m., a shift of 23 minutes in five days. That movement captures not just the volume of orders, but the kind of republic those orders began to build.\
\
The previous period ended with institutions strained but standing. At 7:31 p.m., the system still assumed that constitutional baselines\'97citizenship by birth, two presidential terms, neutral prosecutors, independent inspectors general\'97were hard to move. Week 1 showed how quickly those assumptions could be tested. The new time, 7:55 p.m., reflects a structural turn. Executive power began to operate with less effective oversight. Emergency powers were treated as routine tools. Law was used more as a weapon than a limit. The civil service and internal watchdogs were recast as obstacles to be purged or privatized. Most of all, the meaning of citizenship itself was put on the table, and the formal project of loosening presidential term limits began. The clock moved because these were not symbolic gestures alone; they were backed by orders, deployments, and bills that, if left in place, would be hard to reverse.\
\
The sharpest break with the past came in the attempt to rewrite who counts as an American. On his first day, Trump signed an order titled \'93Protecting the Meaning and Value of American Citizenship,\'94 declaring that children born in the United States to mothers unlawfully present, or to parents without citizenship or permanent residency, would no longer receive automatic citizenship. Parallel versions of this policy appeared across the week: White House releases, Federal Register entries, and public framing that birthright citizenship had been \'93misinterpreted\'94 for generations. The order instructed agencies to withhold documents from these children and set a 30\uc0\u8209 day clock for implementation. Civil rights groups and a coalition of states sued almost immediately. Within days, federal judges in Washington and Seattle, including a Reagan appointee, issued temporary restraining orders, calling the move \'93blatantly unconstitutional.\'94 For the moment, the Fourteenth Amendment held. But the presence of the threat changed the landscape. Citizenship, once treated as a settled birthright, was now something a president claimed the power to narrow by fiat.\
\
Alongside this, the administration moved to stratify belonging in other ways. Asylum and refugee protections were suspended or sharply curtailed. The CBP One app, which had allowed migrants to schedule lawful entry appointments, was shut down without warning, canceling roughly 30,000 bookings and leaving hundreds of thousands in limbo along the border. The \'93Remain in Mexico\'94 policy was reinstated, forcing asylum seekers to wait in dangerous conditions outside U.S. territory. Expedited removal was restored nationwide, allowing ICE to deport people who could not prove two years\'92 presence without full hearings. Arrests in schools, churches, and hospitals\'97long treated as \'93sensitive locations\'94\'97were authorized again. A new Laken Riley Act, passed by both chambers and sent to Trump\'92s desk, mandated detention of undocumented people charged with certain crimes and empowered state attorneys general to sue the federal government for perceived under\uc0\u8209 enforcement. In Mississippi, a legislator proposed cash bounties for \'93illegal alien\'94 deportations. Together, these moves did more than tighten enforcement. They built a layered system in which legal status, place of birth, and even proximity to enforcement sites determined how much protection a person could expect from the law.\
