\
The way law was used in Week 1 also changed. The most visible example was the mass clemency for January 6 participants. On Inauguration Day and in the days that followed, Trump issued \'93full, complete and unconditional\'94 pardons or commutations for more than 1,500 people convicted or charged in connection with the Capitol attack, including leaders of extremist groups and many who assaulted police officers. He ordered the Department of Justice to dismiss pending cases. In interviews, he described the violence as \'93very minor\'94 and cast the rioters as \'93hostages.\'94 Law enforcement unions, federal judges, and even some Republican officials condemned the move, warning that it undermined the rule of law and endangered officers. Yet the pardons stood. At the same time, Trump pardoned anti\uc0\u8209 abortion activists convicted under the FACE Act and Ross Ulbricht, the founder of the Silk Road drug marketplace. In parallel, he signed an order pausing enforcement of the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act, instructing DOJ to halt prosecutions of Americans accused of bribing foreign officials until new guidance was written. Taken together, these acts sent a clear signal: crimes committed in service of the leader\'92s narrative or by those aligned with his interests would be forgiven or deprioritized, while law would be sharpened against opponents.\
