Looking ahead from Week 1, several processes were already in motion. The lawsuits over birthright citizenship, asylum suspensions, and DEI dismantling would move through the courts, testing how far doctrine could restrain executive ambition. The new January 6 subcommittee in the House would begin its work, seeking to rewrite the narrative of the attack. The Laken Riley Act awaited Trump\'92s signature, poised to harden detention rules and invite state lawsuits over immigration enforcement. The Federal Election Commission\'92s closed meeting on enforcement and litigation would proceed, largely out of public view. The Federal Emergency Management Agency Review Council would begin its assessment, with the potential to recommend structural changes that could weaken or reshape FEMA. And the proposed amendment to allow a third Trump term would sit in Congress, a marker of intent even if it never advanced.\
